Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry all
produce. Trim, peel, and cut @carrots{12%ounce} on a diagonal into
½-inch-thick pieces. Finely chop @cilantro{1/4%ounce}. Zest and quarter
@lemon{1} (for 4 servings, zest 1 lemon and quarter both). Peel and mince or
grate @garlic{1%clove}.

Toss carrots on a foil-lined #baking sheet{} with a large drizzle of
@olive oil{2%teaspoon}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}. Roast on top rack until
golden brown and softened, ~{20-25%minutes}.

While carrots roast, in a #small bowl{}, combine cilantro, half the cumin (you'll
use the rest later), half the lemon zest, juice from half the lemon (whole
lemon for 4 servings), 2 TBSP olive oil (4 TBSP for 4), and up to half the
garlic to taste. Season with salt, pepper, and @chili flakes{1%teaspoon} to
taste.

Heat a #small pot{} over medium-high heat. Add 1 TBSP @butter{1%tablespoon}
(2 TBSP for 4 servings), @Israeli couscous{1/2%cup}, and remaining garlic.
Cook, stirring often, until garlic is fragrant and couscous is lightly toasted,
~{1-2%minutes}. Stir in ¾ cup water (1 1/2 cups for 4) and @veggie stock concentrate{1}.
Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until al dente,
~{6-8%minutes}. Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

While couscous cooks, pat @barramundi{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}. Season
generously with remaining cumin, salt, and pepper. Heat a large drizzle of
olive oil in a large, preferably nonstick, pan over medium-high heat. Add
barramundi and cook until opaque and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes} per side.
Turn off heat.

Fluff couscous with a #fork{}; stir in @garlic herb butter{2%tablespoon} and season
with salt and pepper. Toss carrots with remaining lemon zest. Divide couscous,
carrots, and barramundi between plates. Top barramundi with chimichurri. Serve
with remaining lemon wedges on the side.

> We're all about chimichurri these days. It's bright, tangy, herbaceous, and
> so versatile. Cilantro, garlic, lemon, cumin, and chili flakes provide punchy
> flavors that lift everything they touch to new delicious heights.

> The flavors are so harmonious, once you take a bite, you may find it
> impossible to put your fork down.